    Creating

    The primary goal of exoatlas is to create populations of exoplanets which which we can interact in fairly standardized way. Here we summarize a few different pre-defined Population objects we can create.

    In[1]:
    Copied! 
    import exoatlas as ea

ea.version()
    import exoatlas as ea ea.version()
    Out[1]:
    '0.3.7'

    Throughout this page we'll use handy physical_summary() wrapper as a way to visualize some of the basic properties of a particular population. For more on useful plots and plotting tools, see Visualizing.

    Solar System

    The eight planets in our own Solar System are useful as a comparison sample. Their properties are built-in with exoatlas, so they don't need to be downloaded from any archive.

    In[2]:
    Copied! 
    solar = ea.SolarSystem()
solar
    solar = ea.SolarSystem() solar
    Out[2]:
    <Solar System | population of 8 planets>
    In[3]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary(solar);
    ea.physical_summary(solar);

    Confirmed Planets

    The NASA Exoplanet Archive maintains a list of confirmed transiting exoplanets. These are systems that have been published in the peer-reviewed literature. Most of them have been characterized in sufficient detail that they are unlikely to be false positives.

    This archive contains planets discovered through a variety of methods. We can access all exoplanets in the archive, regardless of discovery method, with:

    In[4]:
    Copied! 
    exoplanets = ea.Exoplanets()
exoplanets
    exoplanets = ea.Exoplanets() exoplanets
    Out[4]:
    <Exoplanets | population of 5638 planets>

    For many purposes, it will be really handy to have just those exoplanets that transit their stars. To access those:

    In[5]:
    Copied! 
    transiting = ea.TransitingExoplanets()
transiting
    transiting = ea.TransitingExoplanets() transiting
    Out[5]:
    <Transiting Exoplanets | population of 4220 planets>
    In[6]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary(transiting);
    ea.physical_summary(transiting);

    Kepler vs. Non-Kepler

    Which planets were discovered by Kepler or not?

    In[7]:
    Copied! 
    kepler = ea.Kepler()
kepler
    kepler = ea.Kepler() kepler
    Out[7]:
    <Kepler | population of 3300 planets>
    In[8]:
    Copied! 
    nonkepler = ea.NonKepler()
nonkepler
    nonkepler = ea.NonKepler() nonkepler
    Out[8]:
    <Non-Kepler | population of 920 planets>
    In[9]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary([kepler, nonkepler]);
    ea.physical_summary([kepler, nonkepler]);

    TESS vs. Non-TESS

    Which planets were discovered by TESS or not?

    In[10]:
    Copied! 
    tess = ea.TESS()
tess
    tess = ea.TESS() tess
    Out[10]:
    <TESS | population of 446 planets>
    In[11]:
    Copied! 
    nontess = ea.NonTESS()
nontess
    nontess = ea.NonTESS() nontess
    Out[11]:
    <TESS | population of 3774 planets>
    In[12]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary([nontess, tess]);
    ea.physical_summary([nontess, tess]);

    Space vs. Ground

    Which planets were discovered from telescopes in space or telescopes on the ground?

    In[13]:
    Copied! 
    space = ea.Space()
space
    space = ea.Space() space
    Out[13]:
    <Space-based | population of 3782 planets>
    In[14]:
    Copied! 
    ground = ea.Ground()
ground
    ground = ea.Ground() ground
    Out[14]:
    <Ground-based | population of 438 planets>
    In[15]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary([space, ground]);
    ea.physical_summary([space, ground]);

    Good vs Bad Mass?

    Which planets have masses that have been detected at better than $2.5\sigma$?

    In[16]:
    Copied! 
    good = ea.GoodMass(sigma=2.5)
good
    good = ea.GoodMass(sigma=2.5) good
    Out[16]:
    <Good Mass | population of 966 planets>
    In[17]:
    Copied! 
    bad = ea.BadMass(sigma=2.5)
bad
    bad = ea.BadMass(sigma=2.5) bad
    Out[17]:
    <Bad Mass | population of 3254 planets>
    In[18]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary([bad, good]);
    ea.physical_summary([bad, good]);

    From all these basic populations, you can make your own to play with by indexing, slicing, or masking as described in Exploring. Have fun!
